import folium
from geopy.distance import geodesic

# Latitude and longitude for Crescent City, CA and Monterey, CA
crescent_city_coords = (41.7547, -124.2026)
monterey_coords = (36.6002, -121.8947)

# Calculate the distance between the two locations
distance = geodesic(crescent_city_coords, monterey_coords).miles

# Create a folium map centered between the two locations
m = folium.Map(location=[(crescent_city_coords[0] + monterey_coords[0]) / 2, (crescent_city_coords[1] + monterey_coords[1]) / 2], zoom_start=6)

# Add markers for Crescent City and Monterey
folium.Marker(crescent_city_coords, tooltip="Crescent City, CA").add_to(m)
folium.Marker(monterey_coords, tooltip="Monterey, CA").add_to(m)

# Create a line between the two locations to show the distance
line = folium.PolyLine([crescent_city_coords, monterey_coords], color='blue', weight=2, opacity=1)
line.add_to(m)

# Display the distance as a tooltip on the line
line.add_child(folium.Tooltip(f"Distance: {distance:.2f} miles"))

# Display the map
m.save('geospatial_distance_map.html')

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt


#double backslashes in path to file
path_to_file = "C:\\Users\\cbeau\\Downloads\\WATER LEVELS CRESENT CITY.csv"
Tide_Crescent_City_Ca = pd.read_csv(path_to_file)

path_to_file2 = "C:\\Users\\cbeau\\Downloads\\WATER LEVELS MONTEREY.csv"
Tide_Monterey_Ca = pd.read_csv(path_to_file2)

#Seperate Date Column in to year month day columns
Tide_Crescent_City_Ca['year'] = pd.to_datetime(Tide_Crescent_City_Ca['Date']).dt.year
Tide_Crescent_City_Ca['month'] = pd.to_datetime(Tide_Crescent_City_Ca['Date']).dt.month
Tide_Crescent_City_Ca['day'] = pd.to_datetime(Tide_Crescent_City_Ca['Date']).dt.day

# Split 'Time (GMT)' into 'hour,' 'minute,' and 'second' columns
Tide_Crescent_City_Ca['hour'] = pd.to_datetime(Tide_Crescent_City_Ca['Time (GMT)']).dt.hour
Tide_Crescent_City_Ca['minute'] = pd.to_datetime(Tide_Crescent_City_Ca['Time (GMT)']).dt.minute
Tide_Crescent_City_Ca['second'] = pd.to_datetime(Tide_Crescent_City_Ca['Time (GMT)']).dt.second

# Combine 'year,' 'month,' 'day,' 'hour,' 'minute,' and 'second' into a datetime column
Tide_Crescent_City_Ca['datetime'] = pd.to_datetime(Tide_Crescent_City_Ca[['year', 'month', 'day', 'hour', 'minute', 'second']])


#Seperate Date Column in to year month day columns
Tide_Monterey_Ca['year'] = pd.to_datetime(Tide_Monterey_Ca['Date']).dt.year
Tide_Monterey_Ca['month'] = pd.to_datetime(Tide_Monterey_Ca['Date']).dt.month
Tide_Monterey_Ca['day'] = pd.to_datetime(Tide_Monterey_Ca['Date']).dt.day

# Split 'Time (GMT)' into 'hour,' 'minute,' and 'second' columns
Tide_Monterey_Ca['hour'] = pd.to_datetime(Tide_Monterey_Ca['Time (GMT)']).dt.hour
Tide_Monterey_Ca['minute'] = pd.to_datetime(Tide_Monterey_Ca['Time (GMT)']).dt.minute
Tide_Monterey_Ca['second'] = pd.to_datetime(Tide_Monterey_Ca['Time (GMT)']).dt.second

# Combine 'year,' 'month,' 'day,' 'hour,' 'minute,' and 'second' into a datetime column
Tide_Monterey_Ca['datetime'] = pd.to_datetime(Tide_Monterey_Ca[['year', 'month', 'day', 'hour', 'minute', 'second']])

# Create line plots for water levels over time
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
plt.plot(Tide_Crescent_City_Ca['datetime'], Tide_Crescent_City_Ca['Verified (ft)'], label='Crescent City, CA')
plt.plot(Tide_Monterey_Ca['datetime'], Tide_Monterey_Ca['Verified (ft)'], label='Monterey, CA')

# Customize the plot
plt.title('Monterey and Cresent City CA: Water Levels')
plt.xlabel('Date and Time')
plt.ylabel('Water Level (ft)')
plt.grid(True)
plt.legend()

# Show the plot
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Calculate sample mean
sample_mean_CC = np.mean(Tide_Crescent_City_Ca['Verified (ft)'])
sample_mean_M = np.mean(Tide_Monterey_Ca['Verified (ft)'])
# Calculate sample standard deviation
sample_std_CC = np.std(Tide_Crescent_City_Ca['Verified (ft)'])
sample_std_M= np.std(Tide_Monterey_Ca['Verified (ft)'])
print("SAMPLE MEAN CC", sample_mean_CC)
print("SAMPLE MEAN M", sample_mean_M)
print("SD CC", sample_std_CC)
print("SD M", sample_std_M)

# Initialize an array to store the z-scores
CC_z_scores_array = np.zeros(Tide_Crescent_City_Ca['Verified (ft)'].shape)

# Calculate the z-scores for each data point and store them in the z_scores_array
for i in range(Tide_Crescent_City_Ca['Verified (ft)'].shape[0]):  # Loop through each data point
    CC_z_scores_array[i] = (Tide_Crescent_City_Ca['Verified (ft)'][i] - sample_mean_CC) / sample_std_CC
# Initialize an array to store the z-scores
M_z_scores_array = np.zeros(Tide_Monterey_Ca['Verified (ft)'].shape)

# Calculate the z-scores for each data point and store them in the z_scores_array
for i in range(Tide_Monterey_Ca['Verified (ft)'].shape[0]):  # Loop through each data point
    M_z_scores_array[i] = (Tide_Monterey_Ca['Verified (ft)'][i] - sample_mean_M) / sample_std_M
    

# Scatter plot of z-scores for Crescent City, CA and Monterey, CA
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
plt.scatter(CC_z_scores_array, M_z_scores_array, alpha=0.5)
plt.title('Scatter Plot of Cresent City and Monterey Z-Scores')
plt.xlabel('Crescent City, CA Z-Scores')
plt.ylabel('Monterey, CA Z-Scores')
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()


# Calculate the correlation coefficient between z-scores
correlation_coefficient = np.corrcoef(CC_z_scores_array, M_z_scores_array)[0, 1]

# Scatter plot of z-scores
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
plt.scatter(CC_z_scores_array, M_z_scores_array, alpha=0.5)
plt.title('Scatter Plot of Cresent City and Monterey Z-Scores')
plt.xlabel('Crescent City, CA Z-Scores')
plt.ylabel('Monterey, CA Z-Scores')
plt.grid(True)

# Plot a dashed line with the estimated correlation coefficient as the slope
plt.plot(CC_z_scores_array, correlation_coefficient * CC_z_scores_array, 'k--')

plt.show()

print(f"Estimated Correlation Coefficient (ρ^1,2): {correlation_coefficient:.2f}")

# Maximum lag in terms of time (M∆t) and time increment (∆t)
M = 4  # Adjust this value to limit the maximum lag to < 5 days 
delta_t = 1  # Time increment in days

# Calculate the time lags (τ) for each lag (m)
time_lags = np.arange(-M, M + 1) * delta_t

# Initialize arrays to store the autocorrelation values
auto_corr_CC = np.zeros(2 * M + 1)
auto_corr_M = np.zeros(2 * M + 1)

# Calculate the autocorrelation for each lag (m)
for m in range(-M, M + 1):
    auto_corr_CC[m + M] = np.correlate(CC_z_scores_array, np.roll(CC_z_scores_array, -m)) / (len(CC_z_scores_array) * np.var(CC_z_scores_array))
    auto_corr_M[m + M] = np.correlate(M_z_scores_array, np.roll(M_z_scores_array, -m)) / (len(M_z_scores_array) * np.var(M_z_scores_array))

# Plot the autocorrelation functions
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.plot(time_lags, auto_corr_CC, label='Crescent City, CA', linestyle='-', color='blue')
plt.plot(time_lags, auto_corr_M, label='Monterey, CA', linestyle='--', color='red')
plt.title('Lagged Auto-Correlation Function')
plt.xlabel('Time Lag (days)')
plt.ylabel('Auto-Correlation')
plt.grid(True)
plt.legend()
plt.show()

# Maximum lag in terms of time (M∆t) and time increment (∆t)
M = 23  # Adjust this value to limit the maximum lag to < 24 hours (1 day)
delta_t = 1  # Time increment in hours

# Calculate the time lags (τ) for each lag (m)
time_lags = np.arange(-M, M + 1) * delta_t

# Initialize an array to store the cross-correlation values
cross_corr = np.zeros(2 * M + 1)

# Calculate the cross-correlation for each lag (m)
for m in range(-M, M + 1):
    cross_corr[m + M] = np.correlate(CC_z_scores_array, np.roll(M_z_scores_array, -m)) / (len(CC_z_scores_array) * np.std(CC_z_scores_array) * np.std(M_z_scores_array))

# Plot the cross-correlation function
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.plot(time_lags, cross_corr, label='Cross-Correlation', linestyle='-', color='green')
plt.title('Lagged Cross-Correlation Z-Scores')
plt.xlabel('Time Lag (hours)')
plt.ylabel('Cross-Correlation')
plt.grid(True)
plt.legend()
plt.show()

# Find the maximum cross-correlation and its corresponding time lag
max_corr = np.max(cross_corr)
max_corr_index = np.argmax(cross_corr)
time_lag_with_max_corr = time_lags[max_corr_index]

print(f"Maximum Cross-Correlation (max(ρ^1,2)): {max_corr:.2f}")
print(f"Time Lag at Maximum Cross-Correlation: {time_lag_with_max_corr} hours")

# Maximum Cross-Correlation (max(ρ^1,2)) and Time Lag at Maximum Cross-Correlation
max_cross_corr = 0.98
time_lag_max_corr = -10  # Time lag in hours

# Calculate the time lags (τ) for each lag (m)
M = len(M_z_scores_array) - 1
delta_t = 1  # Time increment in days
time_lags = np.arange(-M, M + 1) * delta_t

# Calculate z2(n+mmax)
z2_n_mmax = np.roll(M_z_scores_array, time_lag_max_corr)

# Scatter plot of z2(n+mmax) versus z1
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
plt.scatter(CC_z_scores_array, z2_n_mmax, alpha=0.5)
plt.title('Scatter Plot of z2(n+mmax) versus z1')
plt.xlabel('Crescent City, CA Z-Scores')
plt.ylabel('Monterey, CA Z-Scores (n+mmax)')
plt.grid(True)

# Plot a dashed line with the slope of max(ρ^1,2)
plt.plot(CC_z_scores_array, max_cross_corr * CC_z_scores_array, 'k--')

plt.show()

tau_max_hours = -10  # Time lag in hours
delta_x_km = 605.93  # Distance in kilometers

# Convert time lag to seconds
tau_max_seconds = tau_max_hours * 3600  # 1 hour = 3600 seconds

# Convert distance to meters
delta_x_meters = delta_x_km * 1000  # 1 kilometer = 1000 meters

# Earth's gravitational acceleration (m/s²)
g = 9.81

# Calculate the wave speed (c) using the distance and time lag
c = delta_x_meters / tau_max_seconds

# Calculate the average depth of the ocean (d)
d = c**2 / g

# Print the results
print(f"Wave Speed (c): {c} m/s")
print(f"Average Depth of the Ocean (d): {d} meters")
